Delete Rows where participants were unable to load or play game, had issues with the survey loading, or failed an attention check (144 people). Also delete rows where participants recorded gender as “Other” (2 people).

data<-data[-which(data$Removedata == "Yes"), ]
data<-data[-which(data$Sex == "Other"), ]

Remove individuals that have a relationship status of ‘other’ (13 individuals)

data = subset(data, Relationshipstatus %in% c("Single", "In an open relationship/casually dating", "In a long-term monogamous relationship eg. married, partnered", "Recently single/divorced/separated"))

Subset data into the three experiments

data_gaming = subset(data, study=="Gaming_manipulation")
data_rank = subset(data, study=="Rank_manipulation")
data_faces = subset(data, study=="Face_choice")
Adding in any functions
Multiple plot function
ggplot objects can be passed in …, or to plotlist (as a list of ggplot objects) - cols: Number of columns in layout - layout: A matrix specifying the layout. If present, ‘cols’ is ignored. If the layout is something like matrix(c(1,2,3,3), nrow=2, byrow=TRUE), then plot 1 will go in the upper left, 2 will go in the upper right, and 3 will go all the way across the bottom.
```r multiplot <- function(…, plotlist=NULL, file, cols=1, layout=NULL) { library(grid)
# Make a list from the … arguments and plotlist plots <- c(list(…), plotlist)
numPlots = length(plots)
# If layout is NULL, then use ‘cols’ to determine layout if (is.null(layout)) { # Make the panel # ncol: Number of columns of plots # nrow: Number of rows needed, calculated from # of cols layout <- matrix(seq(1, cols * ceiling(numPlots/cols)), ncol = cols, nrow = ceiling(numPlots/cols)) }
if (numPlots==1) { print(plots[[1]])
} else { # Set up the page grid.newpage() pushViewport(viewport(layout = grid.layout(nrow(layout), ncol(layout))))
# Make each plot, in the correct location for (i in 1:numPlots) { # Get the i,j matrix positions of the regions that contain this subplot matchidx <- as.data.frame(which(layout == i, arr.ind = TRUE))
print(plots[[i]], vp = viewport(layout.pos.row = matchidx\(row, layout.pos.col = matchidx\)col)) } } } ```

Experiment 2: Rank Manipulation

Are self-scores correlated with the rank they are randomly given in the game

selfrank_corr <- lm(Selfscore  ~  Rank + Sex + VorNV + Age + Rank*Sex + Rank*VorNV, data = data_rank)
anova(selfrank_corr, test="Chisq")
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: Selfscore
##             Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(>F)

## Sex          1   97.66  97.660 53.7236 6.657e-13 ***
## VorNV        1    1.10   1.103  0.6069   0.43624

LT Faces and age

Figure12 <- ggplot(data_faces, aes(x = Age, y = TotalLTScore, color = Sex, shape = Sex, linetype = Sex)) + 
  geom_point(size = 4) + 
  scale_colour_hue(l=50, guide = FALSE) +
  theme_bw() + geom_smooth(method=lm,  fullrange=T) + 
  xlab("Age") +
  ylab("Long-term Facial Preference for masculinity") + 
  theme(legend.position="right") +
  theme(axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"),
        axis.text=element_text(size=18),
        axis.title=element_text(size=20,face="bold"),
        axis.title.y=element_text(vjust=0.25),
        axis.title.x=element_text(vjust=0.25),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.border = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank())
